ARGUMENTS
  directory    App directory to use

FLAGS
  -a, --app, --application <app>  Gadget app to use
  -c, --configure <editor>        Write editor debug config files (vscode, cursor)
  -e, --env, --environment <env>  Environment to use
  -p, --port <port>               Local port for the CDP proxy

EXAMPLES
  $ ggt debugger
  $ ggt debugger --port 9230
  $ ggt debugger --configure vscode
  $ ggt debugger --configure cursor
  $ ggt debugger --app myApp --env development
  $ ggt debugger --port 9230 --configure vscode

Run ggt debugger --help for more information.
"
`;

exports[`root > when deploy is given > prints the usage when --help is passed 1`] = `
"Deploy an environment to production

Performs a two-step process: first pushes your local file changes to the environment,
then deploys that environment to production. If local and environment files have
diverged since the last sync, you'll be prompted to push your local changes and discard
the environment's changes before the deploy proceeds. Use --force to skip this prompt.

USAGE
  ggt deploy [flags]

FLAGS
  -a, --app, --application <app>
        Gadget app to use. The app slug is the subdomain portion of your app URL
        (e.g., my-app from my-app.gadget.app). Can be omitted when
        .gadget/sync.json already records the app.

  -e, --env, --environment, --from <env>
        Environment to deploy from. The source development environment whose
        files and schema will be deployed to production. Defaults to the
        environment recorded in .gadget/sync.json.

  -f, --force
        Skip the push confirmation prompt. Any conflicting changes on the
        environment are discarded without prompting.

ADDITIONAL FLAGS
      --allow <flag,...>
        Enable allow flags (comma-separated)

      --allow-all
        Enable all --allow-* flags

      --allow-charges
        Allow deploying with new charges. Use this flag in CI/CD pipelines to
        skip the interactive billing confirmation prompt that appears when a
        deploy would add charges to your plan.

      --allow-data-delete
        Allow deploying with data loss. Removed models and fields have their
        production data permanently deleted. Without this flag, the deploy is
        blocked when removals are detected.

      --allow-different-app
        Allow syncing with a different app. Overrides the app recorded in
        .gadget/sync.json with the one specified by --app. Use this when you
        want to reuse an existing directory for a different app.

      --allow-problems, --allow-issues
        Allow deploying with problems. Problems include Gelly errors, TypeScript
        errors, and missing references. Without this flag, the deploy is blocked
        until all issues are resolved.

      --allow-unknown-directory
        Allow syncing to an existing directory. Normally, a directory must be
        empty or already contain .gadget/sync.json. Use this when you want to
        initialize sync in a directory with existing content.

EXAMPLES
  $ ggt deploy
  $ ggt deploy --env staging
  $ ggt deploy --force --allow-all
  $ ggt deploy --force --allow=problems,charges,data-delete
  $ ggt deploy --env staging --force --allow-problems --allow-charges --allow-data-delete

CI/CD USAGE
  In non-interactive environments, pass --allow-all or individual
  --allow-* flags to skip interactive prompts:

    ggt deploy --force --allow-all
    ggt deploy --force --allow=problems,charges,data-delete
    ggt deploy --force --allow-problems --allow-charges --allow-data-delete

SEE ALSO
  ggt problems — Check for errors before deploying.
  ggt push — Upload files without deploying to production.
"
`;

exports[`root > when deploy is given > prints the usage when -h is passed 1`] = `
"Deploy an environment to production

USAGE
  ggt deploy [flags]

FLAGS
  -a, --app, --application <app>          Gadget app to use
  -e, --env, --environment, --from <env>  Environment to deploy from
  -f, --force                             Skip the push confirmation prompt

EXAMPLES
  $ ggt deploy
  $ ggt deploy --env staging
  $ ggt deploy --force --allow-all
  $ ggt deploy --force --allow=problems,charges,data-delete
  $ ggt deploy --env staging --force --allow-problems --allow-charges --allow-data-delete

Run ggt deploy --help for more information.
"
`;

exports[`root > when dev is given > prints the usage when --help is passed 1`] = `
"Sync files and stream logs locally

Watches your local files and your Gadget environment for changes, syncing them
bidirectionally in real time. This lets you develop with your preferred editor while
keeping your environment up to date.

On first run, or when files have diverged since the last sync, an initial reconciliation
is performed. You must resolve any conflicts before continuous syncing begins.

While running, application logs are streamed to the terminal unless --no-logs is passed.

USAGE
  ggt dev [directory] [flags]

ARGUMENTS
  directory
        Directory to sync files to. If the directory does not exist, it will be
        created. Defaults to the current working directory when omitted.

FLAGS
  -a, --app, --application <app>
        Gadget app to use. The app slug is the subdomain portion of your app URL
        (e.g., my-app from my-app.gadget.app). Can be omitted when
        .gadget/sync.json already records the app.

  -e, --env, --environment <env>
        Environment to use. Defaults to the development environment. Production
        is read-only for most commands.

  -l, --log-level <level>
        Minimum log level to display. One of: trace, debug, info, warn, error.
        Defaults to info. Use trace or debug for verbose troubleshooting output.

  -m, --my-logs
        Show only logs emitted by your code. Filters out built-in platform logs,
        showing only logs sourced from your own code.

      --no-logs
        Don't stream logs while syncing. Useful when you only need file sync
        without log output, for example when running alongside a separate ggt
        logs session or in a background terminal.

      --prefer <source>
        Auto-resolve conflicts using the given source. Use 'local' to keep your
        local file contents or 'environment' to keep the environment's version.
        Without this flag, you are prompted to choose for each conflict.

ADDITIONAL FLAGS
      --allow <flag,...>
        Enable allow flags (comma-separated)

      --allow-all
        Enable all --allow-* flags

      --allow-different-app
        Allow syncing with a different app. Overrides the app recorded in
        .gadget/sync.json with the one specified by --app. Use this when you
        want to reuse an existing directory for a different app.

      --allow-unknown-directory
        Allow syncing to an existing directory. Normally, a directory must be
        empty or already contain .gadget/sync.json. Use this when you want to
        initialize sync in a directory with existing content.

      --file-push-delay <ms>
        Delay in ms before pushing file changes. Batches rapid file changes into
        a single push by waiting this long after the last change before sending.
        Increase if you see excessive network requests during bulk edits.
        Defaults to 100ms.

      --file-watch-debounce <ms>
        Debounce in ms for file watch events. How long the file watcher waits
        after the last filesystem event before emitting a change. Helps avoid
        duplicate events from editors that write files in multiple steps.
        Defaults to 300ms.

      --file-watch-poll-interval <ms>
        Interval in ms for polling file changes. How often the file watcher
        polls for changes on filesystems that don't support native events (e.g.
        network drives). Defaults to 3s (3000ms).

      --file-watch-poll-timeout <ms>
        Timeout in ms for file watch polling. How long to wait for a poll cycle
        to complete before timing out. Increase for very large directories where
        polling is slow. Defaults to 20s (20000ms).

      --file-watch-rename-timeout <ms>
        Timeout in ms for detecting file renames. How long to wait for an add
        event to be followed by an unlink event (or vice versa) before treating
        them as separate operations instead of a rename. Defaults to 1.25s
        (1250ms).

EXAMPLES
  $ ggt dev
  $ ggt dev ~/gadget/my-app
  $ ggt dev --prefer local
  $ ggt dev ~/gadget/my-app --app my-app --env development --prefer local

IGNORING FILES
  Add a .ignore file (uses .gitignore syntax) to exclude files and folders from syncing.
  These paths are always excluded:

    • .DS_Store
    • .gadget
    • .git
    • .shopify
    • node_modules

LIMITATIONS
  • Only syncs with development environments.
  • Only supports yarn v1 for installing dependencies.
  • Do not delete or move all files at once while syncing.
"
`;

exports[`root > when dev is given > prints the usage when -h is passed 1`] = `
"Sync files and stream logs locally

USAGE
  ggt dev [directory] [flags]

ARGUMENTS
  directory    Directory to sync files to

FLAGS
  -a, --app, --application <app>  Gadget app to use
  -e, --env, --environment <env>  Environment to use
  -l, --log-level <level>         Minimum log level to display
  -m, --my-logs                   Show only logs emitted by your code
      --no-logs                   Don't stream logs while syncing
      --prefer <source>           Auto-resolve conflicts using the given source

EXAMPLES
  $ ggt dev
  $ ggt dev ~/gadget/my-app
  $ ggt dev --prefer local
  $ ggt dev ~/gadget/my-app --app my-app --env development --prefer local

Run ggt dev --help for more information.
"
`;

exports[`root > when env is given > prints the usage for create when --help is passed 1`] = `
"Create a new environment

The environment name is lowercased automatically. Use --from to clone an
existing environment's data and schema; if omitted, the current environment
is used as the source. Use --use to switch your local directory to the
new environment immediately after creation.

See also: ggt add environment for a simpler shorthand that clones
the current environment and auto-switches.

USAGE
  ggt env create <name> [flags]

ARGUMENTS
  name
        New environment name. The name is lowercased automatically. Must be
        unique within the app.

FLAGS
  -a, --app, --application <app>
        Gadget app to use. The app slug is the subdomain portion of your app URL
        (e.g., my-app from my-app.gadget.app). Can be omitted when
        .gadget/sync.json already records the app.

  -u, --use
        Switch to the new environment after creation. Updates .gadget/sync.json
        to point at the new environment so subsequent commands target it.

      --from <env>
        Clone from an existing environment. Clones the source environment's data
        and schema. If omitted, the current environment is used as the source.

EXAMPLES
  $ ggt env create staging
  $ ggt env create staging --from development
  $ ggt env create my-feature --use
"
`;

exports[`root > when env is given > prints the usage for create when -h is passed 1`] = `
"Create a new environment

USAGE
  ggt env create <name> [flags]

ARGUMENTS
  name        New environment name

FLAGS
  -a, --app, --application <app>  Gadget app to use
  -u, --use                       Switch to the new environment after creation
      --from <env>                Clone from an existing environment

EXAMPLES
  $ ggt env create staging
  $ ggt env create staging --from development
  $ ggt env create my-feature --use

Run ggt env create --help for more information.
"
`;

exports[`root > when env is given > prints the usage for delete when --help is passed 1`] = `
"Delete an environment

Prompts for confirmation before deleting unless --force is passed. The
production environment cannot be deleted. If your sync directory was using
the deleted environment, you'll need to switch to another with
ggt env use.

USAGE
  ggt env delete <name> [flags]

ARGUMENTS
  name
        Environment name. The production environment cannot be deleted.

FLAGS
  -a, --app, --application <app>
        Gadget app to use. The app slug is the subdomain portion of your app URL
        (e.g., my-app from my-app.gadget.app). Can be omitted when
        .gadget/sync.json already records the app.

  -f, --force
        Skip confirmation. Deletes the environment immediately without a
        confirmation prompt.

EXAMPLES
  $ ggt env delete staging
  $ ggt env delete staging --force
"
`;

exports[`root > when env is given > prints the usage for delete when -h is passed 1`] = `
